## 5. Build a custom eHOMD database for EMU

This section builds a custom EMU-compatible database using eHOMD 16S rRNA reference sequences and the eHOMD taxonomy table.

### 5.1 Prepare the working directory

```bash
conda activate EMU

mkdir -p "$HOME/emu_databases/eHOMD_build"
cd "$HOME/emu_databases/eHOMD_build"
```

Download the following files from eHOMD:

```text
HOMD_16S_rRNA_RefSeq_V16.03_full.fasta
HOMD_taxon_table2026-02-20_1771618639.txt
```

The exact file names may change with future eHOMD releases. Keep the release/version number in the file name whenever possible.

---

### 5.2 Prepare `taxonomy.tsv`

The eHOMD taxonomy file may contain an initial descriptive line before the actual table header. Remove that line:

```bash
tail -n +2 HOMD_taxon_table2026-02-20_1771618639.txt > taxonomy.tsv
```

Check the first lines:

```bash
head -n 3 taxonomy.tsv
```

Expected structure:

```text
tax_id    Domain    Phylum    Class    Order    Family    Genus    Species    Subspecies
HMT-001   Bacteria  ...
```

If the first column is named differently, for example `HMT-ID`, rename it to `tax_id` manually or with `awk`.

EMU requires numeric taxonomic IDs. Convert `HMT-580` to `580` in the first column:

```bash
awk 'BEGIN{FS=OFS="\t"} NR==1 {print; next} NR>1 {gsub("HMT-", "", $1); print}' taxonomy.tsv \
  > taxonomy_numeric.tsv
```

Check the result:

```bash
head -n 3 taxonomy_numeric.tsv
```

Expected example:

```text
tax_id    Domain    Phylum    Class    Order    Family    Genus    Species    Subspecies
001       Bacteria  ...
580       Bacteria  ...
```

The leading zeros are acceptable as text IDs, but for consistency with the sequence-to-taxonomy map it is often cleaner to remove leading zeros:

```bash
awk 'BEGIN{FS=OFS="\t"} NR==1 {print; next} NR>1 {$1=$1+0; print}' taxonomy_numeric.tsv \
  > taxonomy_numeric_nozeros.tsv
```

Use `taxonomy_numeric_nozeros.tsv` in the final database build.

---

### 5.3 Prepare `seq2tax.map.tsv`

EMU needs a two-column, tab-separated file mapping each sequence ID in the FASTA file to a numeric taxonomic ID.

The FASTA headers usually look like this:

```text
>HMT-580_16S000002 ...
```

The sequence ID is:

```text
HMT-580_16S000002
```

The corresponding taxonomic ID should be:

```text
580
```

Create the mapping file:

```bash
grep "^>" HOMD_16S_rRNA_RefSeq_V16.03_full.fasta \
  | sed 's/^>//' \
  | awk 'BEGIN{FS=" "; OFS="\t"} {seq=$1; tax=seq; sub(/_.*/, "", tax); gsub("HMT-", "", tax); tax=tax+0; print seq, tax}' \
  > seq2tax.map.tsv
```

Check the output:

```bash
head seq2tax.map.tsv
```

Expected example:

```text
HMT-580_16S000002    580
HMT-001_16S000001    1
```

Check that all tax IDs in `seq2tax.map.tsv` are present in the taxonomy file:

```bash
comm -23 \
  <(cut -f2 seq2tax.map.tsv | sort -n | uniq) \
  <(tail -n +2 taxonomy_numeric_nozeros.tsv | cut -f1 | sort -n | uniq)
```

If the command returns no output, all mapped tax IDs are present in the taxonomy table.

---

### 5.4 Build the custom eHOMD EMU database

```bash
emu build-database eHOMD_EMU_DB \
  --sequences HOMD_16S_rRNA_RefSeq_V16.03_full.fasta \
  --seq2tax seq2tax.map.tsv \
  --taxonomy-list taxonomy_numeric_nozeros.tsv
```

Check the database folder:

```bash
ls eHOMD_EMU_DB
```

Expected files:

```text
species_taxid.fasta
taxonomy.tsv
```

Move the database to your main database directory:

```bash
mkdir -p "$HOME/emu_databases"
mv eHOMD_EMU_DB "$HOME/emu_databases/"
```

Final path:

```text
$HOME/emu_databases/eHOMD_EMU_DB
```

---

## 6. Test the custom database

Run EMU on a small control FASTA or on the original eHOMD FASTA to confirm that the database works.

```bash
emu abundance HOMD_16S_rRNA_RefSeq_V16.03_full.fasta \
  --db "$HOME/emu_databases/eHOMD_EMU_DB" \
  --type map-ont \
  --threads 8 \
  --output-dir test_eHOMD_db \
  --output-basename eHOMD_control \
  --keep-counts
```

Expected output:

```text
test_eHOMD_db/eHOMD_control_rel-abundance.tsv
```

If this runs without errors, the custom database is correctly formatted.

