## 7. Run EMU on long-read ONT 16S data

For Oxford Nanopore full-length 16S reads, use:

```bash
--type map-ont
```

This is the default EMU long-read ONT mode, but it is good practice to state it explicitly.

### 7.1 Run one sample

```bash
conda activate EMU

DB_PATH="$HOME/emu_databases/eHOMD_EMU_DB"
OUTPUT_DIR="$HOME/Long_reads_Saliva_16S/emu_outputs/long_reads_eHOMD"
THREADS=16

mkdir -p "$OUTPUT_DIR"

emu abundance sample_filtered.fastq \
  --db "$DB_PATH" \
  --type map-ont \
  --output-dir "$OUTPUT_DIR" \
  --output-basename sample_filtered \
  --keep-files \
  --keep-counts \
  --keep-read-assignments \
  --output-unclassified \
  --min-abundance \
  --threads "$THREADS"
```

Main output:

```text
sample_filtered_rel-abundance.tsv
```

---

### 7.3 Batch run for barcode folders

Use this when each barcode is a folder containing one or more FASTQ files.

```bash
#!/bin/bash
set -euo pipefail

BASE_DIR="$HOME/Long_reads_Saliva_16S/fastq_pass/Barcodes_Marisabel"
OUTPUT_DIR="$HOME/Long_reads_Saliva_16S/emu_outputs/long_reads_eHOMD"
DB_PATH="$HOME/emu_databases/eHOMD_EMU_DB"
THREADS=16

mkdir -p "$OUTPUT_DIR"

for folder in "$BASE_DIR"/barcode*; do

    sample=$(basename "$folder")
    echo "Processing $sample"

    emu abundance "$folder"/*.fastq \
        --db "$DB_PATH" \
        --type map-ont \
        --output-dir "$OUTPUT_DIR" \
        --output-basename "$sample" \
        --keep-files \
        --keep-counts \
        --keep-read-assignments \
        --output-unclassified \
        --min-abundance \
        --threads "$THREADS"

    echo "Finished $sample"

done
```

